{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Log entries with the same trace ID are grouped together across different emitting microservices.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"A pure unit test of grouping logic can miss real failures in wiring between ingestion/parsing/normalization and the correlator (for example, service-specific field mapping differences). No OS/network dependency is required, so System is unnecessary.","test_description":"Run the real ingestion + parse + correlation modules on a mixed fixture set from multiple services, where identical trace IDs appear in different service payload shapes. Assert one correlated group per trace ID and that no entries with that trace ID are split across groups.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.35,"Integration":0.6,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.005,"Workflow":0.005}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"Timeline view orders events by timestamp while tolerating up to 500ms inter-service clock skew.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Ordering with skew is deterministic, but failures often occur at module boundaries (timestamp parsing, normalization, ordering, and timeline assembly). A single-function unit test may miss those boundary bugs.","test_description":"Feed parsed logs from multiple services with controlled skew (<=500ms and >500ms edge cases) through the real timeline assembly path. Assert rendered/produced sequence matches expected causal order policy and that skew tolerance is applied correctly.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.4,"Integration":0.55,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.005,"Workflow":0.005}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"A latency spike is flagged when p99 exceeds 3x baseline.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The statistical rule is deterministic, but real failures are commonly in baseline window computation, percentile aggregation, and anomaly report wiring across modules. Mocking these seams can hide failures.","test_description":"Use the real metrics aggregation + anomaly detection + report generation modules on synthetic latency streams with known baseline and induced spike. Assert p99 calculation and that the anomaly report includes the expected spike flag only when threshold is crossed.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.3,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.005,"Workflow":0.005}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"Malformed JSON entries are skipped safely and counted, without pipeline crash.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Crash-resilience and skipped-count reporting are cross-module behaviors (reader/parser/error handling/counters). Unit-only parser tests can miss pipeline-level termination or counter propagation bugs.","test_description":"Execute the real ingestion pipeline on a batch containing valid and malformed JSON lines. Assert process completes, malformed lines are excluded from downstream correlation, and skipped-entry count equals the malformed input count.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.73,"System":0.06,"Agentic":0.005,"Workflow":0.005}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Sustains bursts of 10,000 log entries/second without drops or lag accumulation.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"This is a runtime throughput/backpressure property that depends on real process scheduling, queues, I/O behavior, and timing under load. In-process mocks can easily hide real dropping/lag failures.","test_description":"Run the tool as a real process with a load generator producing 10,000 structured entries/sec for a sustained interval. Measure input vs processed counts, queue depth/backlog, and end-to-end lag over time; fail if any entry is dropped or lag exceeds defined steady-state bounds.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.2,"System":0.77,"Agentic":0.005,"Workflow":0.005}}]}
